         <div type="edition">
                <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr><supplied reason="lost">S</supplied></abbr><ex>acrum</ex></expan>.
                    <lb n="2"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="praenomen" key="Gnaeus">
                     <expan><abbr>Cn</abbr><ex>aeus</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Aius">A<choice>
                        <corr>i</corr>
                        <sic>t</sic>
                     </choice>us</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Felix">Fel<hi rend="ligature">i<unclear>x</unclear>
                     </hi>
                  </name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="3"/>vixit <expan><abbr>anni</abbr><ex>s</ex></expan>
               <num xml:lang="lat" value="19">XIX</num>.
                    <lb n="4"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Charis">Charis</name>
               </persName> filio <expan><abbr>b</abbr><ex>ene</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>erenti</ex></expan>.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>[Sacred] to the Divine Spirits. Gnaeus A⸢i⸣us Felix lived for nineteen years. Charis (made this) for (her) well-deserving son.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The E in "Felix" (line 2) doesn't have a crossbar. </p>
            <p>According to Tuck, Schulze believes "Atus" to be a variant of "Atius."</p>
            <p>Line 2: Aius (EDR).</p>
         </div>
